<P>
DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: 3 PLEAD INNOCENT IN MARIJUANA FARM CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three people accused of acting as a sales team for a network of underground 
marijuana farms in the Antelope Valley and Arizona pleaded not guilty Thursday 
to felony charges. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Kumar, 31; Gabriel Alfred, 29; and Elizabeth Haskell, 26, were charged 
with one count each of conspiracy to sell marijuana and conspiracy to possess 
marijuana for sale. 
</P>
<P>
They were arrested in connection with the widening investigation into the 
sophisticated farms uncovered in the past month by Los Angeles County sheriff's 
deputies and federal Drug Enforcement Administration agents. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, Haskell and Kumar were charged with one count each of possession 
of marijuana for sale. 
</P>
<P>
The three were arrested Nov. 30 in Castaic after Kumar allegedly attempted to 
buy 30 pounds of marijuana for $105,000 from undercover sheriff's deputies. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities have said they suspect Kumar of being the top distributor of 
marijuana grown in the high-tech farms allegedly built and operated by a group 
of construction contractors. He is in jail in lieu of $1-million bail. 
</P>
<P>
Alfred and Haskell are free on $75,000 and $50,000 bail, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
