<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
BUSINESSES SPROUT IN GERMANY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BERLIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 226,000 new private businesses were registered in eastern Germany in 
the first 10 months of this year, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
Klaus Solveen, head of the Economic Ministry's eastern German office in Berlin, 
said the creation of new businesses accelerated after East and West Germany 
merged their economies on July 1 as a prelude to political union on Oct. 3. 
</P>
<P>
A total of 226,652 businesses were registered by Oct. 31, more than a quarter 
of them in the depressed industrial state of Saxony, Solveen told the German 
press agency ADN. 
</P>
<P>
About 113,000 of the new businesses were restaurants and retail outlets, while 
33,000 were involved in handicrafts and 2,000 were related to tourism. 
</P>
<P>
Revival of small- and medium-sized business in formerly Communist eastern 
Germany is viewed as crucial to turning around an economy floundering from mass 
shutdowns of state-owned industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
