<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
CHINA HIKES COST OF TICKETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BEIJING 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government said today it will double city bus fares and raise by 20 
times the cost of tickets for the Great Wall in the new year -- the first hikes 
in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
Beijing residents reacted to the increases with dismay and voiced fears of a 
resurgence in 1991 of inflation, which soared to 18% in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Bus and trolley fares will double from the equivalent of one U.S. cent to two 
cents and underground fares will rise from six cents to 10 cents. 
</P>
<P>
The huge increases were the first since fares and park entrance fees were 
introduced 40 years ago, the state-run New China News Agency quoted a city 
official as saying. 
</P>
<P>
Admission tickets to most parks and tourist sites, including the Great Wall and 
the Summer Palace will go up from two cents to 40 cents. Between 30,000 and 
40,000 people visit the Summer Palace each day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
